### CHAPTER XCVIII.

1\. The ninety-eighth subject is this, that it is necessary for all
those of the good religion, that they learn the Avesta characters *in*
the presence of

<span id="page_360">p. 360</span>

priests *and* teachers, so as to read, *and that* no error *may*
continue *in* the Nyâyi*s*es and Ya*s*ts.

2\. And it is still more expedient for priests *and* teachers, that they
teach the Avesta characters to all those of the good religion <span
id="fr_1580"></span>[1](#fn_1569.md): and if a priest, while teaching,
shows incompetence (taqʓîr), it is a great sin for him. 3. For Hôrmazd,
the good *and* propitious, spoke to Zaratu*s*t thus: '*As to* every
priest and teacher *who* commits a blunder in teaching <span
id="fr_1581"></span>[2](#fn_1570.md) those of the good religion, I make him
just as far from heaven as the width of the earth <span
id="fr_1582"></span>[3](#fn_1571.md).'

